sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K145005
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: cI under control of a dual promotor and a RiboLock.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: Verify the dual promotor. Check if transcription can still proceed from the T7 promotor when cI is bound.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Jonas Demeulemeester

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: cI lam
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: A synthetic oscillatory network of transcriptional regulators , Elowitz M.B. , Leibler S., Nature(403),335-38: 2000
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: The cI regulated promoter is based on the pR promtoer from bacteriohage lambda. The promoter has two two DNA binding sites for lambda cI repressor BBa_C0051. cI binding results in repression of transcription. The specific sequence used here is based on the cI repressible promoter used in the Elowitz repressilator (and references therein).
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
In order to address concerns about the promoter transcribing in the reverse direction, we have removed the -35 and -10 signals responsible for the promoter activity in the reverse direction. (More details needed here! DE, 2/24/03)

Incompatible with host expressing cI repressor.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Vinay S Mahajan, Brian Chow, Peter Carr, Voichita Marinescu and Alexander D. Wissner-Gross

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_I712074
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: T7 promoter (strong promoter from T7 bacteriophage)
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: T7 promoter is very specific promoter which is transcribed only by specific T7 RNA polymerase. Usually this promoter is used in expression systems where T7 promoter is cotransfected with T7 RNA polymerase. That ensures strong transcription of desired genes.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Rok Gaber

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_P0150
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Protein generator converting TIPS to the protein cI (HK022). Used as the input section for Quad Part Inverter Q01500
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Randy Rettberg

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0012
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Derived from the TE terminator of T7 bacteriophage between Genes 1.3 and 1.4 <genbank>V01146</genbank>.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Transcription terminator for the E.coli RNA polymerase.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Suggested by Sri Kosuri and Drew Endy as a high efficiency terminator. The 5' end cutoff was placed immediately after the TAA stop codon and the 3' end cutoff was placed just prior to the RBS of Gene 1.4 (before AAGGAG).

Use anywhere transcription should be stopped when the gene of interest is upstream of this terminator.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Reshma Shetty

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0010
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Transcriptional terminator consisting of a 64 bp stem-loop.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Randy Rettberg

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0031
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Medium RBS based on Ron Weiss thesis. Strength considered relative to <bb_part>BBa_B0030</bb_part>, <bb_part>BBa_B0032</bb_part>, <bb_part>BBa_B0033</bb_part>.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Varies from -6 to +1 region from original sequence to accomodate BioBricks suffix ("RBS-1" in figure 4-14 of thesis).

No secondary structures are formed in the given RBS region. Users should check for secondary structures induced in the RBS by upstream and downstream elements in the +50 to -50 region, as such structures will greatly affect the strength of the RBS.

Contact info for this part: Brian Cho
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Vinay S Mahajan, Voichita D. Marinescu, Brian Chow, Alexander D Wissner-Gross and Peter Carr IAP, 2003.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: cI HK022
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Coding region for the HK022 bacteriophage cI protein. cI binds to the HK022 pR regulator (BBa_R0050). It represses transcription of the protein encoded by the sequence 3' to the pR region. This coding sequence does not contain a RBS.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:

Response from John Little (Arizona) regarding the start of HK022 cI

From:
Date: Tue Jan 21, 2003 4:39:21 PM US/Eastern
To: "Drew Endy"
Subject: RE: hk022 cI start (naive question)?
Hello Drew and Michael, I seriously doubt that the extra 27 aa are part of CI. It doesn't make sense in terms of the biology, for sure. In any case, the protein we characterized starts where Carlson and Little stated; as I recall, oR3 partially overlaps the start of cI. I have a vague memory of some possibly interesting biology, having to do with multicopy plasmids. I don't recall the findings themselves. Anyway, one possible explanation was that this extra N-terminal addition was made (e.g. from the pRE promoter, or from a message that arose from transcription around the entire plasmid), making a protein with altered functions. We never followed it up.
Good luck
John

-- Original Message --
Date: Sun, 19 Jan 2003 15:26:26 -0500
Subject: hk022 cI start (naive question)?
Cc: elowitm@rockefeller.edu
To: jlittle@u.arizona.edu
From: Drew Endy
Hi John, I'm sitting here with Michael Elowitz and we're working through the sequence for HK022 cI. We noticed that the annotation from NC_002166 includes an "extra" 81 base pairs upstream of what we thought of as the actual start. It looks like this extra DNA extends into the PR regulatory region. We're wondering what's going on here? I'm guessing this is well documented somewhere. Thanks for any pointers/info!
Drew

It is unknown whether there is cross-talk between this repressor and Lambda cI regulatory region, 434 cI regulatory region and P22 regulatory region.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Reshma Shetty
